China's love for cars has led to an 80% growth in the car market, making it the world's fourth largest.
However, this has resulted in dangerous roads filled with inexperienced drivers.
The WHO reports that China's road fatalities are based on incomplete data.
Implementing seat belt and helmet laws, cracking down on speeding and drunk driving, and ensuring road visibility can reduce fatalities.
In Argentina, over 7,000 people died in road accidents in 2003.
Strict enforcement of safety measures is crucial to prevent further tragedies.
ASEAN countries are also working towards improving road safety to prevent future accidents and fatalities.
